<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/854698c2717b49e86a960fc6f74b8e99> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Schildering in waterverf en inkt op papier. Religieuze volksschildering, voorstellend de onsterfelijke, Zhang Guolao (Kor.: Chang Kwa-no) op een ezel met twee andere onge√Ødentificeerde onsterfelijken op de achtergrond. Zhang is bekend door de overlevering dat hij achterstevoren op een ezel door het land reed. Zhang zou zich onder meer onzichtbaar kunnen maken en is bekend om zijn wandelstok die ook als fluit gebruikt kan worden. Naast de twee andere onsterfelijken zijn ook een geit en een vliegende draak afgebeeld.\r\nOp de achterkant van het papier staat in een hoek met inkt het Chinese karakter voor '3'.\r\n\r\nZhang Guolao (Chang Kwa- no in Korean pronunciation) is the person with the yuku or bamboo cane in his hands. Zhang Guolao was said to have lived between the 7th and 8th centuries and had the power to render himself invisible. His walking cane, yuku was believed to be a musical wind instrument.  Zhang lives in seclusion on mount Zhong Tiao. During the Tang dynasty, he was already reported to be over 200 years. Once, the Empress Wu Zhe Tiang dispatched officers to call upon him and bring him back for questioning, but he pretended to be dead. Afterwards some people met him walking around Mount Heng. He was invited by Xuan Zong, the Emperor of the Tang dynasty, to demonstrate his magic arts. He typically is pictured riding a white donkey with his back forward. The donkey is capable of running thousands of miles each day. According to the legend, when he needs to rest, he folds up the white donkey and hides it in a small box. \r\nThe two figures in the background are not discernible according to the particular attributes of eight immortals. The directions of the gazes and movements of three figures and three animals - a donkey, a goat, and a dragon - are all different.\r\nDaoist (Taoist) immortals are considered 'patron saints' of the Daoist belief. Their images were representative of typical individuals and represented wealth and poverty, old age, and youth, male and female. It was believed that ordinary human beings could learn the sectets of nature and become immortal, through hard study. These immortals were idolised and respected for their wisdom, humour, and moral lessons. Normally, only eight immortals are officially recognised, but legends describe several more. As the Eight Daoist Immortals to which they belong, these emblems are representations of longevity." .
